hair is \u003Cstrong\u003Ethermoregulation through air trapping\u003C/strong\u003E. Hair creates an insulating layer of still air next to the skin surface, which helps maintain body temperature. This is particularly important in cold environments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPheromone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Although some mammals use hair for pheromone dispersion, this is not a significant function in humans.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtection against infection\u003C/strong\u003E - Hair provides minimal protection against infectious agents and is not considered a significant barrier to infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of sebum\u003C/strong\u003E - Whilst sebaceous glands are associated with hair follicles, sebum production is not a function of the hair itself but rather of the associated glands.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in the deeper layers of the epidermis when exposed to ultraviolet radiation, not in hair structures.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional functions of hair include sensory perception through associated nerve endings and limited protection against ultraviolet radiation and mechanical damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hair provides thermal insulation by trapping air close to the skin surface.","Hair follicles contain sensory nerve endings that detect movement and touch.","Hair protects against ultraviolet radiation and mechanical damage to the skin."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17803"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:45:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:45:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10517"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72443"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and Associated Structures","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"